  <h4>Resistance: Mechanical, Magnetic and Air</h4>
  <p>
    Resistance is what makes your riding harder when pedaling. They help increase the workout intensity and thus create a more realistic or real world riding experience. Generally speaking, there are 3 types of resistance system possible on exercise bikes: mechanical (or Direct-contact), magnetic and air.
  </p>
  <p>
    For <b>mechanical</b> resistance, direct contact with the flywheel creates friction which can be increased or decreased manually, usually by turning a knob. The direct contact braking uses the principle of friction to create Resistance.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is done by bringing the brake pads closer to the flywheel. They make contact and this creates resistance when a user pedals on the bike. As the resistance level is increased by the knob, the brake pads become further attached to the flywheel and this creates a higher level of resistance when a user tries to pedal. 
  </p>
  <p>
    This type of exercise bike is very accurate and lets you switch between the various resistance levels until you find one that is just right for you.
  </p>
  <p>
    The brake pads are usually made out of felt, but a number of other materials can be found in its place as well.
  </p>
  <p>
    Alternatively, friction bands can also be used in place of brake pads. They are simply fitted to the edge of the flywheel to cause the same effect of resistance.
  </p>
  <p>
    For all its advantages, exercise bike with direct-contact friction tend to experience a lot of mechanical abuse, which causes them to wear out over time. Eventually, the brake pads or the flywheel itself may have to be replaced. 
    Furthermore, due to the fact that the braking system is purely mechanical, direct-contact exercise bikes tend to make noise, unlike bikes with magnetic braking.
  </p>
  <p>
    <b>Magnetic Resistance</b>
     is relatively new to the market than mechanical. It is the most functional resistance system in the market and this is because it uses electromagnetic Induction to confer resistance on the flywheel. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Magnets are placed at different locations in order to create a Magnetic Brake pad. Unlike mechanical the magnetic brake pad does not make contact with the flywheel, instead it generates a magnetic field when it reaches certain proximity with the flywheel. 
  </p>
  <p>
    The effect of the magnetic field gets stronger (and thus creates more resistance is created) as the proximity of the flywheel increases.
    Changes with proximity can be made via buttons on the console and magnetic resistance works excellently with heart rate control and pre-set workouts.
  </p>
  <p>
    Because the magnets and the flywheel do not have direct contact or touch in this resistance system, their parts don’t wear or tear. As such Magnetic resistance rarely needs replacement of it flywheel or parts.
  </p>
  <p>
    Stationary bikes with magnetic braking have a very smooth, continuous resistance, which can be adjusted at the touch of button, and they are extremely quiet. In fact, they are quieter than both direct-contact and fan exercise bicycles. They are the best of the three and most popular
  </p>
  <p>
    Last but not the least, <b>Air or Fan-based Resistance Bike</b>; This system of resistance doesn’t make use of a flywheel instead a huge resistance fan is found where the flywheel would normally be. The fan itself is connected to the pedals via belt and pulley system.
  </p>
  <p>
    <b>Air</b>
    resistance works by your pedaling powering the fan which generates an air flow. The quicker you pedal the harder the resistance. One issue with air resistance is that it’s directly linked to your speed, so the only way to lower the resistance is to pedal slower. On the plus side, you get to feel the breeze from the fan which cools you down during intense workout session. In other words, the air resistance does have some sort of inbuilt cooling system.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each of this resistance system is great and although we do have our favorite (Magnetic), I don’t think you can go wrong by selecting any one of them. This should purely be based on your budget.
  </p>
  <p>
    Exercise bikes that use a brake-based design are usually cheaper than magnetic resistance bikes. It is sturdy and simple in it construction, and while there is not much that can go wrong there you still need to maintain and replace some parts once in a while.
  </p>
  <p>
    Magnetic exercise bikes require less maintenance and make less noise.
  </p>
  <p>
    Fan Bikes are a totally different topic on their own. They brought a totally different form of resistance into the game.
  </p>
  <p>
    So whichever resistance system you choose to go for, there isn’t much that can go wrong.
  </p>
